ce:section.ce:para:
Immunotherapy is an essential and unique approach to the treatment of cancer and infectious diseases, where immune activation is required, but also in inflammatory and allergic disorders, where immune suppression is needed. It presents high specificity, long-term efficacy, reduces the need for high quantities of drugs and provides less invasive treatments, comparing to traditional therapies. The use of CNM, alone or as drug carriers, to modulate the immune response has great potential for clinical application, as discussed in the previous sections. However, important questions remain about the long-term effects of the presence of the CNM on the human body. The following points summarize the current challenges to translating the CNM results for immunotherapy, reviewed in the previous sections, into clinical applications, which have not been achieved yet:

                           •

Overcome the concerns related to CNM toxicity and biodegradability;


                           •

Maximize the synergistic effects and minimize the side effects of CNM-mediated immunotherapy;


                           •

Understand the context of an organ-specific tumour/disease for an effective therapy;


                           •

Translate the results obtained in animal models into human applications;
